The problem asks to prove that there exist $b, N$ such that for all $n > m \ge N$, $|\sum_{j=m+1}^n (a_j - b)| \le 1007^2$.
This is IMO 2015 Problem 6.

We choose $b$ to be the number of "holes" in the range of the map $c_k = k + a_k$. Since $1 \le a_k \le 2015$, the number of holes is bounded (specifically by 2015) and the set of holes $H$ is finite.
Let $E_n = \sum_{k \le n, c_k > n+b} c_k - \sum_{k > n, c_k \le n+b} c_k$.
We show that $\sum_{j=1}^n (a_j - b) = C + E_n$ for some constant $C$ and sufficiently large $n$.
Then we bound $E_n$ by considering the maximum possible value of the difference of sums of two disjoint sets of size $q_n$, subject to the constraints imposed by $a_k \in [1, 2015]$.
The bound is maximized when $q_n \approx 2014/2 = 1007$, yielding $1007^2$.

